description: A large aisled building revealed during excavations at Colchester House, near the Tower of London in 1993. It has been suggested that the layout is comparable to the Cathedral of St. Tecla, Milan. It is not certain whether this is a church or some kind of public storage space.
bibliography: Shepherd, J., Hall, J., (2008), Places of worship in Roman London and beyond, in Ritual Landscapes of Roman South-East Britain
Sankey, D., (1998), Cathederals, granaries, and urban vitality in late Roman London, in Roman London: Recent Archaeological Work, pg. 78-82
